<DOC><DOCNO> AP880610-0057 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-10-88 0401EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     06-10 0759</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Political Briefs,760</SECOND><HEAD>Dukakis To Hold Meeting on Drugs</HEAD><DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Likely Democratic presidential nomineeMichael Dukakis is planning a meeting with Florida Attorney GeneralBob Butterworth and about a half-dozen state and federal officialsnext week in Boston to discuss ways to battle the nation's drugproblems.   Dukakis, who already has won enough delegates to capture hisparty's nomination during first-round convention balloting, iscalling on Butterworth for advice partly because of his earlycampaign support and because Florida is the top port for thenation's illegal drug imports.   ``The only way we're going to resolve this drug problem is forthe federal government to work with the state government and localofficials. Having been a sheriff, I can say ... the federalgovernment has never been known for its efforts to work with localofficials,'' said Butterworth.   Also planning to attend the policymaking sessions from Floridaare Rep. Larry Smith, D-Hollywood, and Janet Reno, chief prosecutorin the state's drug-ridden Dade County. Reps. Charles Rangel,D-N.Y.; Glenn English, D-Okla.; Thomas Foley, D-Wash.; and Sen.Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz. also are expected to attend.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Wisconsin Governor Suggests Liz Dole as Bush Running Mate</HEAD><DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Gov. Tommy G. Thompson says Elizabeth Dole,former U.S. transportation secretary, would make an ideal runningmate for Vice President George Bush in his presidential bid.   ``She's an outstanding person, a fine speaker and would bringsome pizazz to the ticket,'' said Thompson Thursday.   The Wisconsin chief executive is a long-time Bush supporter forthe Republican presidential nomination, who will head the statedelegation to Republican National Convention in New Orleans inAugust. Bush won the Wisconsin's 47 convention delegates.   Elizabeth Dole is the wife of Sen. Robert Dole, R-Kan., whodropped out of the presidential primary races about a week beforeWisconsin's April 5 primary.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Statehouse Becomes Choice Site for Protests Against Dukakis</HEAD><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A group of supporters of presidential candidateJesse Jackson are expected to bring their concerns to the frontdoorsteps of the likely Gov. Michael Dukakis when they gather atthe Massachusetts Statehouse today.   An ad-hoc group including many members of Massachusetts' RainbowCoalition plan to gather at the Statehouse to urge DemocraticNational Chairman Paul Kirk to meet with them and consider ways toincorporate the Jackson movement into the party platform and,possibly, into the ticket.   The Statehouse has in recent days become a focal point forgripes against the likely Democratic presidential nominee.   On Thursday, representatives of the minority-dominated NewAlliance Party held a small rally in front of the Statehouse. Partychairwoman Emily Carter called Dukakis ``the `first striker' whoseidea of good government is currying favors from big business andwho is the author of an executive order making it practicallyimpossible for lesbians and gays in Massachusetts to become fosterparents.''</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Education Secretary Rips Democrats At State GOP Convention</HEAD><TEXT>   HOUSTON _ U.S. Education Secretary William J. Bennett says heswitched political parties two years ago because the Democrats areout of touch with the average American.   In a speech to the Texas GOP state convention Thursday, Bennettsaid Democrats today are on the wrong side of such issues asdefense, economic growth and traditional values.   ``This is the sad truth: the Democratic leadership today is anuncertain ally in the defense of freedom in in the world. Itwavers, it is weak, it is not resolute, it shirks rather thanembraces our duty,'' he said.   Bennett, who said he was the only Democrat in President Reagan'scabinet when he joined it three and one half years ago, said he nowbelieves that party has a warped view of the nation's future.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Annual Virginia GOP Convention Opens Today</HEAD><DATELINE>ROANOKE (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Virginia Republicans will end their search for aU.S. Senate candidate this weekend, but a breakfast fund-raiser onSaturday may draw more interest than the state GOP Conventionitself.   Delegates to the convention, which opens later today, have athree-way choice to replace Sen. Paul S. Trible Jr., who surprisedparty leaders last fall when he said he would not seek a secondterm.   Vying for the Senate nomination are Andrew F. Wahlquist, aformer aide to Republican Sen. John W. Warner; Gil Faulk, a McLeanattorney; and Maurice Dawkins, a northern Virginia businessman.   Wahlquist is believed to be favored by most rank-and-filedelegates, but some party leaders like the idea of nominatingDawkins, who is black, to challenge the minority support expectedto go to Democratic nominee former Gov. Charles S. Robb.</TEXT></DOC>